  SOLUTION 



(a) Using the Pythagorean Identity \sin^2{ ( \theta )} + \cos^2{ ( \theta ) } =1, we can solve for \cos{ ( \theta )}:
\cos^2{ ( \theta ) } = 1 - \sin^2{ ( \theta ) } = 1 - \left( \frac{x}{5} \right)^2 = \frac{ 25 - x^2}{25}.
Since the angle \theta is in the first quadrant, \cos{ ( \theta ) } \ge 0, so \cos{ ( \theta ) } = \sqrt{ \frac{ 25 - x^2}{25} }



(b) \tan{ (  \theta ) } = \frac{ \sin{ ( \theta )}}{\cos{ ( \theta )}} = \frac{\frac{x}{5}}{\sqrt{\frac{ 25 - x^2}{25}} } = \frac{x}{\sqrt{25 - x^2}}

  SOLUTION 



(a) Using the Pythagorean Identity \sin^2{ ( \theta )} + \cos^2{ ( \theta ) } =1, we can solve for \cos{ ( \theta )}:
\cos^2{ ( \theta ) } = 1 - \sin^2{ ( \theta ) } = 1 - \left( \frac{x}{6} \right)^2 = \frac{ 36 - x^2}{36}.
Since the angle \theta is in the first quadrant, \cos{ ( \theta ) } \ge 0, so \cos{ ( \theta ) } = \sqrt{ \frac{ 36 - x^2}{36} }



(b) \tan{ (  \theta ) } = \frac{ \sin{ ( \theta )}}{\cos{ ( \theta )}} = \frac{\frac{x}{6}}{\sqrt{\frac{ 36 - x^2}{36}} } = \frac{x}{\sqrt{36 - x^2}}
